A diffuse goiter that is not associated with changes in thyroid function or malignancy.

Pulmonary emphysema in which the changes are noted throughout a secondary pulmonary lobule, particularly in the lower lobes of the lung.

A rare vascular condition in the liver in which the hepatic sinusoids proliferate and become engorged. Though it is often an incidental finding, it may be associated with certain medications, infections, transplants, malignancy, hematologic disorders, and autoimmune conditions.
Inflammation of the portal vein.

A stroke syndrome caused by infarction of the cerebral territories supplied by the posterior cerebral artery (PCA). Signs and symptoms may include visual field deficits, agnosia, aphasia and memory deficits.

A syndrome caused by insult to the posterior columns of the spinal cord and resulting in impairments of proprioception, vibration, and fine touch. Typical presenting signs and symptoms may include sensory ataxia, dizziness, unsteady gait, and frequent falls.

A more severe form of premenstrual syndrome (PMS) with more extreme mood and physical symptoms. As with PMS, symptoms begin prior to an individual's menstrual cycle and typically taper off as menstruation begins.
The consideration of societal factors as variables in disease incidence, transmission, and control.

A neurological condition caused by scarring and degeneration of the temporal lobe. It is characterized by cognitive and behavioral symptoms, and focal epilepsy.

A neurological condition experienced by individuals with epilepsy, in which a seizure is followed by a brief period of temporary paralysis.

Any mutation that occurs within the discrete sequences comprising the 5' or 3' splice sites of a gene that has a spliced message. Splice-site mutation may result in a deletion or insertion of extraneous amino acids in the gene product or a change in the reading frame of the spliced message.
